I think the first part is a genuinely interesting model of learning.

Not literally that we forget exactly one-third, but that loss and reconstruction are often where abstraction comes from.

If a student memorizes every move in a chess game, they have a record.

If they forget most of the moves but retain the pattern, they may have learned strategy.

If an engineer forgets the details of a hundred projects but remembers the recurring failure modes, they’ve extracted an invariant.

In that sense, learning often looks like:

Experience → Compression → Loss → Reconstruction → Insight

The loss isn’t always a bug.

Sometimes it’s what forces the mind to discover a more general rule.

That’s one reason analogies, stories, and simplified models can be so powerful. They deliberately discard detail to preserve structure.

